The 24th Ward’s first black alderman, who liked being known as the "Big Cat" and the "Duke of Dixieland," won a second term in 1963. But just two days later, on Feb. 28, 1963, police found Ald. Ben Lewis handcuffed to a chair at ward headquarters, with three bullet holes in his head. Even for a city known for mob-style killings, Lewis’ murder was big news. One by one, lie detector tests were administered to potential suspects: the janitor who found Lewis’ body; the janitor’s helper; customers with a beef about his business practices; rebel precinct captains; political rivals; fired patronage workers; disappointed job-seekers; policy-wheel operators; mobsters; the gangster’s wife he’d supposedly made a pass at; his girlfriends; his ex-wife; and his wife. His murder is still unsolved.
Ald. Ben Lewis, the 24th Ward's first black alderman who was first elected to his seat in 1959, in an undated photo.
Ella Lewis testifies on the witness stand at the inquest for her murdered husband, Ald. Ben Lewis, at the county board room on March 7, 1963.

Brand logos have always had a well-known presence at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. We affiliate the Golden Arches with McDonald's and a simplistic navy blue star with the Dallas Cowboys. But did you know that sounds can be trademarked as well — legally registered as representing a company or product? For example, the Mockingjay whistle from "The Hunger Games." And why not? After all, Hasbro trademarked the smell of Play-Doh (seriously). Here's a list of some familiar sounds that have been trademarked by their brands. Brand logos have always had a well-known presence at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. We affiliate the Golden Arches with McDonald's and a simplistic navy blue star with the Dallas Cowboys. But did you know that sounds can be trademarked as well — legally registered as representing a company or product? For example, the Mockingjay whistle from "The Hunger Games." And why not? After all, Hasbro trademarked the smell of Play-Doh (seriously). Here's a list of some familiar sounds that have been trademarked by their brands. Click the links in each caption to hear the sound.

Remember during the polar vortex when many Chicago businesses let their employees work from home and we nearly lost our minds after two days of despair and distraction? #NeverForget. To remedy the stir-crazy the next time you're allowed to work remotely, we've rounded up some quiet, quaint and creative locales through the city worth checking out.

Brand logos have always had a well-known presence at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. We affiliate the Golden Arches with McDonald's and a simplistic navy blue star with the Dallas Cowboys. But did you know that sounds can be trademarked as well — legally registered as representing a company or product? For example, the Mockingjay whistle from "The Hunger Games." And why not? After all, Hasbro trademarked the smell of Play-Doh (seriously). Here's a list of some familiar sounds that have been trademarked by their brands. To remedy the stir-crazy the next time you're allowed to work remotely, we've rounded up some quiet, quaint and creative locales through the city worth checking out.

Brand logos have always had a well-known presence at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. We affiliate the Golden Arches with McDonald's and a simplistic navy blue star with the Dallas Cowboys. But did you know that sounds can be trademarked as well — legally registered as representing a company or product? For example, the Mockingjay whistle from "The Hunger Games." And why not? After all, Hasbro trademarked the smell of Play-Doh (seriously). Here's a list of some familiar sounds that have been trademarked by their brands. Click the links in each caption to hear the sound.

“New Girl” alum and Chicago-area native Jake Johnson plays first baseman Arnold “Chick” Gandil, who was one of the White Sox players accused of throwing the 1919 World Series.

The Chicago White Sox lost to the Cincinnati Reds during the 1919 World Series and eight players were later accused of fixing the series. The 1921 Black Sox trial acquitted the eight ball players, but they were banned for life from playing professional baseball. The eight acquitted players are White Sox pitcher Eddie Cicotte, first baseman Arnold 'Chick' Gandil, shortstop Charles 'Swede' Risberg, center fielder Oscar 'Happy' Felsch, pitcher Claude 'Lefty' Williams, star outfielder 'Shoeless' Joe Jackson, third baseman George 'Buck' Weaver and utility infielder Fred McMullin. Buck Weaver did not go in on the fix, but he knew of the plan and was therefore banned due to this knowledge.

French food is resurgent coast-to-coast, Tribune restaurant critic Phil Vettel observed in a review of Brindille restaurant in January. Indeed, with new restaurants like Le Sud, "one of the bright surprises of last year," Vettel wrote, and seasoned chef Michael Lachowicz converting his Restaurant Michael into two new spots, Aboyer and Silencieux, while maintaining his four-star,  Jean Banchet Restaurant of the Year George Trois, French cuisine is everywhere in the news. So for April, our "Craving" series spotlights all food French, from classic to modern.

Remember during the polar vortex when many Chicago businesses let their employees work from home and we nearly lost our minds after two days of despair and distraction? #NeverForget. To remedy the stir-crazy the next time you're allowed to work remotely, we've rounded up some quiet, quaint and creative locales through the city worth checking out.

Brand logos have always had a well-known presence at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. We affiliate the Golden Arches with McDonald's and a simplistic navy blue star with the Dallas Cowboys. But did you know that sounds can be trademarked as well — legally registered as representing a company or product? For example, the Mockingjay whistle from "The Hunger Games." And why not? After all, Hasbro trademarked the smell of Play-Doh (seriously). Here's a list of some familiar sounds that have been trademarked by their brands. Click the links in each caption to hear the sound.

Off-duty Chicago police Officer Michael Bailey, 62, was gunned down outside his South Side home in July 2010. Bailey was still in uniform after finishing an overnight shift and was washing his Buick Regal car. Prosecuters say Anton Carter, now 31, attempted to rob Bailey, sparking the shootout in which Bailey died. Carter will stand trial this week for Bailey's killing.
Anton Carter, also known as Antwon Carter, is set to go on trial for the murder of Chicago police Officer Michael Bailey.
